# API Route Patterns

## Route Handlers
- Every route handler must be an async function wrapped with the `asyncHandler` utility
- Keep handlers thin — extract business logic into service functions
- Validate all input (params, query, body) at the top of each handler using Zod schemas
- Return early on validation failure with a 400 status

## Response Format
- All successful responses must follow: `{ data: T }`
- All error responses must follow: `{ error: string, code: string }`
- Use helper functions `sendSuccess(res, data, status?)` and `sendError(res, message, code, status)`
- Never return raw strings or unstructured JSON

## HTTP Methods and Status Codes
- GET: 200 for success, 404 for not found
- POST: 201 for creation, 409 for conflict (duplicate)
- PATCH: 200 for update, 404 if resource missing
- DELETE: 204 with no body on success
- Always return 401 for unauthenticated and 403 for unauthorized

## Middleware
- Use route-level middleware for auth checks, not global middleware
- Order middleware: auth -> validation -> rate limiting -> handler
- Middleware should call `next()` on success, `next(error)` on failure
- Never modify `req` directly — attach parsed data to `res.locals`

## Error Handling
- Use the centralized error handler in `src/middleware/error-handler.ts`
- Throw `AppError` subclasses from handlers and services — never send raw responses for errors
- Log the full error server-side; send only the safe message to the client
- Catch database constraint violations and map them to user-friendly error codes

## Route Organization
- Group routes by resource: `/api/users`, `/api/posts`, `/api/comments`
- Use `express.Router()` per resource, mounted in `src/routes/index.ts`
- Keep route files focused — one resource per file, max ~100 lines
- Parameterized routes use `:id` naming, validated as UUID or number at parse time
